benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: DELETE /1.0/kb/accounts/{accountId}/customFields - Remove custom fields from account

covered: Valid Deletion: Scenarios TC01 and TC02 validate successful deletion of all or specific custom fields (204) and subsequent GET validation.
Optional Headers: TC03 covers X-Killbill-Reason and X-Killbill-Comment handling.
No Custom Fields: TC04 covers deletion when no fields exist.
Invalid accountId format: TC05 validates 400 on bad UUID format.
Non-Existent Account: TC06 ensures 204 with empty body for non-existent account.
Missing Header: TC07 validates 400 for missing required header.
Invalid customField IDs: TC08 validates 400 for invalid IDs.
Extra Query Parameters: TC09 handles extra params with 204 and proper removal behavior.
Unauthorized Access: TC10 validates 401/403 behavior.
System Error: TC11 validates 500 on dependency failure.
Network Timeout: TC12 validates timeout/504 behavior.
Large Number of IDs: TC13 covers 204 with removal of many IDs.
Duplicate IDs: TC14 confirms 204 with duplicates processed.
Regression: TC15 ensures second delete on already removed field returns 204.
Performance: TC16 tests concurrent deletions with 204 and latency threshold.
Integration: TC17 ensures data consistency post-deletion.
State Variation: TC18 removes only existing fields in partially populated accounts.
Security - SQL Injection: TC19 ensures 400 for invalid accountId input.
Security - XSS in customField: TC20 ensures 400 for invalid input in field.
Comprehensive error scenarios: 400/401/403/500/504 across multiple conditions
gaps: Soft delete semantics not explicitly tested (e.g., tombstone or logical delete indicators).
Caching behavior not tested (ETag, Cache-Control headers) across DELETE operations.
Race condition coverage could be more explicit (e.g., concurrent conflicting deletions on the same account).
Explicit rate-limiting/throttling scenarios (beyond performance/concurrency) are not tested.
recommendations: Add a test ensuring soft-delete semantics or explicit confirmation that records are permanently removed vs. marked deleted.
Include tests verifying caching headers (ETag/Cache-Control) on DELETE responses and subsequent GET behaviors with caching implications.
Introduce explicit race-condition tests for consecutive or overlapping deletes to validate idempotency and proper handling.
Add dedicated rate-limiting/throttling tests (e.g., burst of DELETE requests) to verify resilience under load.
